   <mods:abstract>This arrete, entitled "On the Actual Situation of the Country," begs that
            the King base a lasting liberty, peace, and public wellbeing on the harmony of all the
            orders. Harmony would consist in the natural and constitutional right of citizens to
            choose their deputies, in not arbitrarily determining the number of deputies to the
            general assembly, because their number was never determined bylaw; in calling periodic
            sessions of the States General: in recognizing the right of the States General to draw
            up legislation; in granting subsidies only for a fixed sum and a fixed time; in
            recognizing that the right of allocating funds to each Department belongs to the States
            General; in insuring the protection of the individual liberty of citizens and the rights
            of persons accused of crimes; in insuring the maintenance of freedom of the
            press.</mods:abstract>
